The '''CNP-600''' is a [[pressurized water reactor|pressurized water nuclear reactor]] developed by the [[China National Nuclear Corporation]] (CNNC).<ref>{{cite web|last1=(IAEA)|first1=International Atomic Energy Agency|title=- Nuclear Power - IAEA|url=https://www.iaea.org/NuclearPower/aris/|website=www.iaea.org|accessdate=29 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> The reactor has a gross electrical capacity of 650 MW. It is a [[generation II reactor]] based on China's first commercial nuclear reactor design, the [[CNP-300]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Biello|first1=David|title=China forges ahead with nuclear energy|url=https://www.nature.com/news/2011/110329/full/news.2011.194.html|accessdate=28 May 2018|work=Nature|date=29 March 2011|language=en|doi=10.1038/news.2011.194}}</ref> and on the M310 reactor design used in [[Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant]].<ref>{{cite web|title=China’s commercial reactors|url=https://www.belfercenter.org/sites/default/files/legacy/files/chinas-commercial-reactors-proof.pdf|publisher=Nuclear Engineering International|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>
The first CNP-600 unit began operation at [[Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant]] in 2002, with other 3 units coming online between 2004 and 2011. There are only 2 CNP-600 reactors currently under construction, both at [[Changjiang Nuclear Power Plant]].<ref name=neimag /> An advanced version of the design, the [[ACP-600]], is currently being developed by the CNNC. The new design will have improved safety systems and an extended design life of 60 years.<ref name=neimag>{{cite web|title=Chinese reactor design evolution - Nuclear Engineering International|url=http://www.neimagazine.com/features/featurechinese-reactor-design-evolution-4272370/|website=www.neimagazine.com|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>
