{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox power station | name = Puna Geothermal Venture | name_official = | image = Puna Geothermal plant.webp | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = USA Hawaii | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|19.4785|N|154.8888|W|region:US-HI_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = United States | location = [[Puna, Hawaii]] | status = M | construction_began = 1989 | commissioned = 1993 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = [[Ormat Technologies]] | operator = <!------------------------- GEOTHERMAL POWER STATIONS --> | geo_type = BC | geo_temp_requirement = | geo_well_count = 11 | geo_well_depth = {{convert|8297|ft|m}} | geo_water_output = | geo_cogeneration = | geo_combined_cycle = Yes <!------------------------- GENERAL --> | ps_units_operational = 0 (closed in May 2018 due to nearby eruption) | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | ps_thermal_capacity = | ps_heating_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = 38 | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_storage_hours = | ps_annual_generation = | website = {{url|https://www.hawaiianelectric.com/clean-energy-hawaii/clean-energy-facts/renewable-energy-sources/geothermal/puna-geothermal-venture-(pgv)|hawaiianelectric.com/clean-energy-hawaii/clean-energy-facts/renewable-energy-sources/geothermal/puna-geothermal-venture-(pgv)}} | extra = }} The '''Puna Geothermal Venture''' (PGV) is a currently nonoperational [[geothermal energy]] power plant on the [[Hawaii (island)|island of Hawaii]], the largest island in the state of [[Hawaii]]. The plant was shut down shortly after the start of the May [[2018 lower Puna eruption]]. The eruption caused lava to flow over a power substation, a warehouse and at least three geothermal wells that had been preventatively quenched and capped when [[lava fountain|lava fountain]]s erupted nearby, eventually also cutting off road access.<ref name="staradvertiser.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/27/breaking-news/lava-speeds-up-takes-aim-at-puna-geothermal-wells/|title=Lava speeds up, forcing evacuations and covering well at Puna Geothermal plant|date=May 27, 2018 |newspaper=[[Star Advertiser]] |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/07/08/hawaii-news/geothermal-plant-faces-challenges-amid-uncertainty/|title=Puna Geothermal Venture faces challenges amid uncertainty|date=July 8, 2018 |newspaper=[[Star Advertiser]] |publisher=}}</ref>
PGV was the first and only commercially-productive geothermal electrical plant in Hawaii. Constructed on a site adjacent to failed experimental wells drilled and operated by the Hawaii Geothermal Project in the 1970s and 80s, construction on the generating facility began in 1989 and was completed in 1993.
Prior to the shutdown and lava damage, the plant had an installed generating capacity of 38&nbsp;MW<ref name = "HELCO">{{cite web|url=https://www.hawaiielectriclight.com/clean-energy-hawaii/clean-energy-facts/renewable-energy-and-storage-projects|title=Renewable Energy & Storage Projects|website=www.hawaiianelectric.com}}</ref> from six production wells and five injection wells along [[Kīlauea]]’s East [[rift zone]], which had provided approximately 25% of the island’s power. Power generated was sold to the [[HELCO|Hawaiian Electric Industries]] (also known as HELCO) to supply the island’s electric power customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hawaiianelectric.com/clean-energy-hawaii/clean-energy-facts/renewable-energy-sources/geothermal/puna-geothermal-venture-(pgv)|title=Puna Geothermal Venture (PGV)|website=www.hawaiianelectric.com}}</ref>
==History== ===Early geothermal exploration and development=== The first exploratory geothermal wells in Kapoho were drilled in 1961–62.<ref name="Ormat 2016 PowerPoint"/>{{rp|9}} The effort was spearheaded by wealthy local landowner [[Rufus Anderson Lyman#Children|Richard Lyman]] following a trip to Japan, where he learned of a project to lay underwater power cables between the country's islands. Upon returning to Hawaii, Lyman promoted geothermal electrical generation in the Puna district, distributed to Oahu and other population centers by underwater electric cables, as a way of developing the then-newly-admitted-state's economy. He found business partners to establish Hawaii Magma Power in 1961 to develop geothermal energy in the region. Several exploratory drills were made before the company determined that there was insufficient geothermal potential, although Lyman claimed to the ''Honolulu Advertiser'' that the company "had mechanical difficulties and gave up."<ref name="Szvetecz thesis">{{cite thesis|last1=Szvetecz |first1=Annie |type=MSc thesis |title=Geothermal energy in Hawai'i: an analysis of promotion and regulation |date=August 2001 |publisher=ProQuest LLC |url=https://scholarworks.umt.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=9293&context=etd |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref>{{rp|12–13}}
===Hawaii Geothermal Project=== In the 1970s, the Hawaii Geothermal Project was formed to conduct research funded by federal and state grants.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|13–15}} After scientific studies of the geology and geothermal potential of the area were conducted by HGP, a site for the first well was chosen in 1975. Drilling began without environmental impact studies or a period for public input. At the time, the area around the drill site was very rural and undisturbed, but new subdivisions were planned nearby.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|14–15}} The well was occasionally allowed to discharge gas and fluid from the borehole, which created a loud noise and release large volumes of toxins and pollutants into the air. By 1976, three subdivisions nearby had been established and were beginning to see an influx of residents, including twelve families that now lived within one mile of the well. The continued noise pollution and toxic gas discharges began to cause concern and opposition from the new, nearby residents. Nonetheless, funds were secured from the federal and state governments to begin the next step of the project: turning the geothermal energy of the well into electricity.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|15–19}} Although HELCO was among the stakeholders in the project, they assured their stockholders that they would not invest the company's capital in the project due to the volcanic and seismic risk at the site.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|19}}
An experimental 3&nbsp;MW generator was completed in 1981 and remained operational throughout the 1980s. However, families continued to build and move into the nearby subdivisions, resulting in several attempts and a failed lawsuit to stop the noise and pollution generated from the site.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|20–29}} Since the site was within a high lava hazard zone, the generator was built on skids and housed in a building which included a crane so that the generator could be removed if lava flows threatened the facility.<!-- <ref name="Boyd et al 2002"/>{{rp|13}} --> Additionally, the wellhead was housed in a concrete bunker that could be sealed to prevent lava from damaging the wellhead.<ref name="Boyd et al 2002"/>{{rp|13}} Despite the opposition and the operating losses incurred by operating and maintaining the generator, there was enough support to keep the generator operating. In April 1989, county officials raised concerns about the condition of the facility following a minor blowout and considered reviewing and possibly revoking the operating permit for the site. After several additional incidents at the site in 1989, the facility was ordered to be shut down, which occurred on December 11.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|30–32}} During its life, the HGP generator produced between 15 and 19&nbsp;million [[kilowatt hour]]s of electricity annually.<ref name="Boyd et al 2002"/>{{rp|13}}
===Puna Geothermal Venture=== {{OSM Location map | coord = {{coord|19.47|-154.9}} | zoom = 12 | float = right | width = 280 | height = 200 | caption = | title = | scalemark = 10 |shape = image |mark = black pog.svg |mark-size = 6 |mark-coord= {{coord|19.467971|-154.919341}} |label = Leilani Estates |label-color = black |label-pos=top |mark-title= Leilani Estates |mark-coord1= {{coord|19|23|11|N|155|06|18|W}} |mark-size1 = 6 | mark-size3= 8 | mark3 = red pog.svg | mark-coord3={{coord| 19.478860|-154.888612}} | label3 = Puna Geothermal Venture |label-color3 = black | label-size3 = 12 | label-pos3=bottom |mark-title3= Puna Geothermal Venture }} In 1980, HELCO requested a proposal for 25&nbsp;MW of geothermal electricity generation. To answer the request, a joint venture was formed the same year between two of Lyman's companies and two other companies to produce geothermal energy on a {{convert|500|acre|adj=on}} parcel of land leased from the Lyman family. The joint venture was renamed Puna Geothermal Venture in 1981. Over the following years, PGV drilled three wells, but all suffered from mechanical failures of their well casings and were unusable for production.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|39–41}}
In 1986, PGV secured a contract with HELCO to supply 25&nbsp;MW of electricity by 1993. PGV promised that they would be using new technology that would result in zero emissions and operate at a drastically lower noise level. In 1989, when the HGP facility was facing growing problems, the PGV proposed facility managed to overcome enough local opposition to be granted a permit from the local planning commission.<ref name="Szvetecz thesis"/>{{rp|41–45}}
The plant has raised some concerns with local residents as a result of occasional toxic emissions.<ref name="GTM March 2015"/> In 1991, well KS-8 suffered a [[blowout (well drilling)|blowout]], causing the state to suspend the permits for the plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-hawaii.org/?p=3857|title=At Puna Geothermal Venture, Success Is Always Just Around the Corner|website=www.environment-hawaii.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Essoyan |first1=Susan |title=Blowout Shuts Geothermal Unit in Hawaii |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-06-15/news/mn-503_1_puna-geothermal-venture |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=June 15, 1991}}</ref> In 2016 the plant’s owners were found to be in violation of U.S. [[Environmental Protection Agency]] standards regarding [[hydrogen sulfide]] releases and was fined $76,500 for two incidents in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/epa-finds-puna-geothermal-venture-violated-chemical-safety-rules/1025938733|title=EPA finds Puna Geothermal Venture violated chemical safety rules|first=Web|last=Staff|date=January 12, 2016|publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]] |work=[[KHON2]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |last1=Higuchi |first1=Dean |title=EPA finds Puna Geothermal Venture violated chemical safety rules |url=https://archive.epa.gov/epa/newsreleases/epa-finds-puna-geothermal-venture-violated-chemical-safety-rules.html |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |publisher=EPA |date=January 12, 2016 |location=Honolulu}}</ref> Additional concerns and opposition to the plant have been raised by Native Hawaiians, who view all forms of volcanic activity as manifestations of the goddess [[Pele (deity)|Pele]]. To the Native Hawaiians who revere Pele, geothermal wells and energy production are a desecration of her body and spirit.<ref name="Ormat 2016 PowerPoint"/>{{rp|7}}
In 2005 during the drilling of the KS-13 well, magma was encountered at a depth of {{convert|2488|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}. The borehole had to be redrilled several times as the magma flowed up the borehole, cooling into clear, colorless glass. The magma, at a temperature of approximately 1922°F (1050°C), was [[dacitic]]—similar to the [[granitic]] rock that forms continents—consisting of approximately two-thirds [[silica]], which contrasts with the dark, iron-rich [[basalt|basaltic]] rock that forms most of the Hawaiian Islands. It was encountered after drilling through a {{convert|73|m|order=flip|abbr=on}} layer of [[diorite]] igneous rock, which suggested to researchers that the magma had chemically separated as it dwelled for a long period of time.<ref name="Nature 2008">{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=Rex |title=Drillers hit Hawaiian magma |url=https://www.nature.com/news/2008/081217/full/news.2008.1317.html |accessdate=June 2, 2018 |work=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |date=December 17, 2008 |doi=10.1038/news.2008.1317}}</ref><ref name="AGU Abstract">{{cite web |title=Abstract: Dacite Melt at the Puna Geothermal Venture Wellfield, Big Island of Hawaii |url=http://abstractsearch.agu.org/meetings/2008/FM/V23A-2129.html |website=American Geophysical Union |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Abstract:Dacite Melt at the Puna Geothermal Venture Wellfield, Big Island of Hawaii |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/253714192_Dacite_Melt_at_the_Puna_Geothermal_Venture_Wellfield_Big_Island_of_Hawaii |website=ResearchGate |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name="BBC 2008">{{cite news |last1=Amos |first1=Jonathan |title=Drillers break into magma chamber |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7780873.stm |accessdate=June 2, 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=December 17, 2008}}</ref> As quoted in the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'', the team said it was possibly the first time that "the actual process of differentiation of continental-type rock from primitive ocean basalt has been observed ''in situ''".<ref name="Nature 2008"/> Magma specialist Bruce Marsh of [[Johns Hopkins University]] described the uniqueness of the encounter: "Before, all we had to deal with were lava flows; but they are the end of a magma's life. They're lying there on the surface, they've de-gassed. It's not the natural habitat. It's the difference between looking at dinosaur bones in a museum and seeing a real, living dinosaur roaming out in the field."<ref name="BBC 2008"/>
PGV had a generating capacity of 25&nbsp;MW when it opened in 1993, which was expanded to 30&nbsp;MW in 1995 and 38&nbsp;MW in 2012.<ref name="Ormat 2016 PowerPoint">{{cite web |last1=Schroeder |first1=Martin |title=A Renewable Energy Solution on Hawaii Island – The Puna Geothermal Plant |url=https://www.esmap.org/sites/esmap.org/files/Ormat_World%20Bank%20RE%20Study%20Tour_web.pdf |publisher=Ormat Technologies |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |format=PDF |date=May 27, 2016}}</ref>{{rp|9}} In 2015, HELCO announced that Ormat was selected as the winner of a bid to add 25&nbsp;MW of geothermal generating capacity in the Puna district.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cocke |first1=Sophie |title=Ormat Awarded Big Island Geothermal Contract |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/02/ormat-awarded-big-island-geothermal-contract/ |publisher=Honolulu City Beat |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name="GTM March 2015">{{cite web |last1=Hunt |first1=Tam |title=Is Going Bigger on Geothermal a Good Move for the Big Island? |url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/is-going-bigger-on-geothermal-a-good-move-for-the-big-island#gs.R7mVDxc |publisher=Greentech Media |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |date=March 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Ormat 2016 PowerPoint"/>{{rp|25}} In March 2018, Ormat announced their plan to increase production at the plant by 8&nbsp;MW—from 38&nbsp;MW to 46&nbsp;MW—by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Alice |title=Puna Geothermal Venture Increasing Production |url=https://www.higp.hawaii.edu/hggrc/puna-geothermal-venture-increasing-production/ |publisher=Hawai'i Groundwater & Geothermal Resources Center |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>
===Lava damage and closure in 2018 === {{further|2018 lower Puna eruption}} {| class="wikitable floatright" style="width:240px;" |{{Site plan | marker = Red circle.svg | markersize = 50 | markertext = Puna Geothermal Venture | pos_x = 90 | pos_y = 35 | map = USGS Kīlauea multimediaFile-2079.jpg | mapsize_x = 220 | mapsize_y = 165 | maptext = Click here to expand this image }} |- |Southern part of the Puna Geothermal Venture (red circle) is seen nearby the lava fountains of Kīlauea volcano |} On May 3, 2018 earth fissures opened inside and around the [[Leilani Estates]] subdivision near the PGV plant, following hundreds of earthquakes over the first two days of May, resulting in concerns of possible toxic hydrogen sulfide gas releases and explosions at the geothermal power facility. According to PGV's vice president of community affairs, PGV began preemptively shutting down equipment and inventorying its stockpile of highly-flammable [[pentane]] when the frequency of earthquakes began increasing and the first cracks appeared in Leilani Estates on May 1–2;<!-- semicolon used because both sentences (either side of semi-colon) are according to PGV's vice president of community affairs and share same citation --> the plant was taken off-line approximately three hours after it received the first report that lava had begun to emerge from the ground on May 3.<ref>{{cite web|title=VIDEO: Puna Geothermal Concerns At Eruption Meeting|url=http://www.bigislandvideonews.com/2018/05/05/video-puna-geothermal-concerns-at-eruption-meeting/|publisher=Big Island Video News|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> All pentane stored at PGV, approximately {{convert|60000|USgal}}, were removed by the morning of May 10.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crews remove pentane gas from Puna geothermal plant amid safety concerns|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/38140123/precautionary-measures-taken-at-puna-geothermal-plant-amid-growing-lava-fears|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=Hawaii News Now|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>
Over the next couple of weeks, the wells were quenched with cold water to stabilize them—where the weight of the cold water was sufficient to prevent steam from rising from the bottom of the well—and allow them to be plugged. One well, KS-14, possibly being super-heated from close proximity to magma, could not be quenched and was filled with a [[Drilling fluid|drilling mud]] in an attempt to stabilize it. The wells were then sealed with metallic plugs, which arrived at the site on May 22, that officials with PGV claim can withstand 2000°F (1100°C) lava.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wells are hurriedly plugged at Hawaii power plant under threat of lava flow|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-hawaii-volcano-wells-20180523-story.html|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=AP|date=May 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Burnett|first1=John|title=Official: As lava approaches, workers close to capping geothermal wells|url=http://www.hawaiitribune-herald.com/2018/05/21/hawaii-news/official-as-lava-approaches-workers-close-to-capping-geothermal-wells/|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=Hawaii Tribune Herald|date=May 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name="KHON May 28">{{cite news|title=Puna Geothermal Venture deemed stable after lava covers two wells|url=http://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/puna-geothermal-venture-deemed-stable-after-lava-covers-two-wells/1205182245|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=KHON|date=May 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="HNN">{{cite news|title=State says well field at Puna Geothermal 'essentially safe'|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/38243112/lava-flow-tiptoes-onto-puna-geothermal-plants-property-and-then-stalls|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=Hawaii News Now|date=May 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=VIDEO: As Lava Nears, Officials Working To Kill Geothermal Wells|url=http://www.bigislandvideonews.com/2018/05/21/video-as-lava-nears-officials-working-to-kill-geothermal-wells/|accessdate=May 30, 2018|work=Big Island Video News|date=May 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name="PGV update 21 May">{{cite AV media |people=Tom Travis |date=May 21, 2018 |title=As Lava Nears, Officials Working To Kill Geothermal Wells (May 21, 2018) |type=Press conference recording |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ho6qTgOtx7o |access-date=May 21, 2018 |time= |publisher=Big Island Video News |ref= }}</ref> According to Tom Travis of the Hawaii Emergency Management Agency, he researched and was unable to find any precedent for lava overrunning a geothermal well that had been shut-down like the wells at PGV.<!-- 8:03-8:37 --> The PGV team had spoken with scientists in Iceland that have operated wells within lava fields and provided insights into how lava might affect the wellhead of a shutdown well.<!-- 8:37-9:26 --><ref name="PGV update 21 May"/>{{rp|8:03–9:26}}
Lava approached several of the capped wells on May 27.<ref name="staradvertiser.com"/> Two of the 11 capped geothermal wells, identified as KS-5 and KS-6, were covered by the lava from fissures 7 and 21 on May 27 and 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/38287296/lava-reaches-site-of-puna-geothermal-plant-no-gas-release-detected|title=Lava covers at least 1 well at Puna geothermal plant; governor says risk is 'mitigated' |first=Mileka |last=Lincoln |newspaper=[[Hawaii News Now]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hawaiitribune-herald.com/2018/05/27/hawaii-news/fresh-lava-within-200-yards-of-active-well-at-pgv/ |title=Some Leilani Estates residents ordered to evacuate immediately |newspaper=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]}}</ref> The event was the first time lava had covered a geothermal well.<ref name="reuters">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hawaii-volcano/lava-covers-potentially-explosive-well-at-hawaii-geothermal-plant-idUSKCN1IT0D8|first=Jolyn |last=Rosa |title=Lava covers potentially explosive well at Hawaii geothermal plant|website=Reuters|accessdate=May 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiitribune-herald.com/2018/05/28/hawaii-news/lava-takes-10-homes-inundates-another-geothermal-well/|title=Lava takes 10 homes, covers another geothermal well |newspaper=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]] |first=John |last=Burnett |date=May 28, 2018 |access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref> On May 30 a substation and a warehouse containing a drilling rig were overrun and destroyed by molten rock, with the main access road to the facility cut.<ref>http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/06/01/breaking-news/lava-burns-2-buildings-at-puna-geothermal-plant/</ref> A third well was covered with lava later during the eruption.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/07/08/hawaii-news/geothermal-plant-faces-challenges-amid-uncertainty/|title=Puna Geothermal Venture faces challenges amid uncertainty|date=July 8, 2018 |newspaper=[[Star Advertiser]] |publisher=}}</ref>
Despite the geothermal plant’s shutdown, Hawaii Electric Light did not expect [[Rolling blackout|blackouts]] on the Big Island to be caused by insufficient power generation as older, diesel-fueled generators were brought on-line.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Darrell |title=Officials Say No Risk of Blackout From Lava Breach at Hawaii Geothermal Plant |work=Power Magazine |date=May 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hawaii Electric Light expects sufficient power even with geothermal plant shut do |url=https://www.hawaiielectriclight.com/hawaii-electric-light-expects-sufficient-power-even-with-geothermal-plant-shut-down |publisher=Hawaii Electric Light |date=May 3, 2018 |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref> According to PGV's vice president of community affairs, the wells can be put back into operation.<ref name="KHON May 28"/>
In June 2018, [[Snopes.com]] debunked several [[fake news]] and [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] that were spreading which claimed that '[[Hydraulic fracturing|fracking]]' activity by PGV [[Environmental impact of hydraulic fracturing#Seismicity|caused earthquakes]] in the vicinity and was the main cause of the 2018 lower Puna eruption:<ref name="Snopes fracking">{{cite news |last1=Kasprak |first1=Alex |title=Did Fracking Cause Volcanic Activity on Hawaii’s Big Island? |url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/did-fracking-cause-volcanic-activity-hawaii/ |accessdate=June 27, 2018 |work=[[Snopes.com]] |date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> {{quote|To Exopoltics.org’s credit, it is true that fracking (if it were occurring, which it is not) could cause earthquakes. Unfortunately for their argument, another thing that causes earthquakes is volcanic activity — the very same activity that Exopolitics is trying to blame on PGV. You can’t use the symptom of a lava flow (earthquakes) as evidence that earthquakes (from fracking) caused that lava flow. That’s not how this works. Are there earthquakes in the area of PGV? Certainly. There are earthquakes all over the volcanically active Big Island. Is it shocking that there would be earthquakes focused in the (extremely general) region of PGV? Not at all — recall that PGV’s location was selected due to its ''proximity'' to a major fault system, thereby allowing water to flow through the ground and come in contact with the volcanically heated region below. You cannot use PGV’s location (intentionally placed in an area where earthquakes are common and lava flows likely) as evidence that it caused earthquakes and lava flows. That’s not how this works.<ref name="Snopes fracking"/>}}
==Kapoho Geothermal Reservoir==<!-- "Kapoho Geothermal Reservoir" redirects to this section, if section name is changed, please edit the redirect page --> PGV is located in the East Rift Zone of the [[Kīlauea]] volcano, which forms the Big Island of Hawaii. The geothermal energy reservoir discovered by the Hawaii Geothermal Project in this location is known as the Kapoho Geothermal Reservoir.<ref name="Boyd et al 2002">{{cite journal |last1=Boyd |first1=Tonya L. |last2=Thomas |first2=D. |last3=Gill |first3=A. T. |title=Hawaii and Geothermal-What Has Been Happening |journal=Geo-Heat Center Quarterly Bulletin |date=September 2002 |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=11–21 |url=http://hahaha.typepad.com/files/geoheat.oit.edu-1.pdf |accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>{{rp|11}} The geothermal energy potential of the East Rift Zone is estimated to exceed 200&nbsp;MW.<ref name="EERE pamphlet"/> The geothermal reservoir is contained within basaltic rock and relies on the permeability of two major fracture systems. Both fracture systems have large openings, recorded by the drop of {{convert|8.5|in|abbr=on}} drillbits for up to {{convert|30|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Fitch and Matlick 2008"/>
==Facilities== {{OSM Location map | coord = {{coord| 19.4774|-154.8896}} | zoom = 16 | float = right | width = 280 | height = 240 | caption =Location of plants and well pads<ref name="Ormat 2016 PowerPoint"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Puna Geothermal Venture |website=Hamilton Library, University of Hawai'i at Manoa |url=https://evols.library.manoa.hawaii.edu/handle/10524/46378}}</ref> | title = | scalemark = 100 |shape = image |mark = Red circle (thin).svg |mark-size = 30 |mark-coord= {{coord|19.476992| -154.890651}} |label = Pad A |label-color = black |label-size = 14 |label-pos=top |mark-title= Pad A
|mark-size1 = 30 | mark1 = Red circle (thin).svg | mark-coord1={{coord|19.476832| -154.888251}} | label1 = Pad D |label-color1 = black | label-size1 = 14 | label-pos1=top |mark-title1= Pad D
|mark-size2 = 30 | mark2 = Red circle (thin).svg | mark-coord2={{coord|19.475365| -154.891816}} | label2 = Pad E |label-color2 = black | label-size2 = 14 | label-pos2=top |mark-title2= Pad E
| mark-size3= 30 | mark3 = Red circle (thin).svg | mark-coord3={{coord|19.475501| -154.887556}} | label3 = Pad F |label-color3 = black | label-size3 = 14 | label-pos3=top |mark-title3= Pad F
| mark-size4= 14 | mark4 = green pog.svg | mark-coord4={{coord|19.478386| -154.888423}} | label4 = Combined cycle plant |label-color4 = black | label-size4 = 14 | label-pos4=left |mark-title4= Combined cycle plant
| mark-size5= 14 | mark5 = green pog.svg | mark-coord5={{coord|19.476229| -154.889312}} | label5 = Binary cycle plant |label-color5 = black | label-size5 = 14 | label-pos5=bottom |mark-title5= Binary cycle plant
| mark-size6= 30 | mark6 = Red circle (thin).svg | mark-coord6={{coord|19.478942| -154.887349}} | label6 = Pad B |label-color6 = black | label-size6 = 14 | label-pos6=top |mark-title6= Pad B }} The first and only geothermal energy plant in Hawaii, the plant began generating power in 1993, and is owned by [[Ormat Technologies]] which purchased it in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.higp.hawaii.edu/hggrc/projects/geothermal-digital-collection/geothermal-topic-guides/puna-geothermal-venture/|title=Puna Geothermal Venture - Hawai‘i Groundwater & Geothermal Resources Center|website=www.higp.hawaii.edu}}</ref>
===Power plants=== There are two power plants in the Puna Complex. The first plant consists of ten [[Combined cycle]] [[Ormat Technologies#Thermal Energy |Ormat Energy Converters]] (OEC) made up of ten [[steam turbine]]s and ten [[Binary cycle|binary turbines]].<ref name=ar2017/> Production of electricity began on April 22, 1993.<ref name="EERE pamphlet">{{cite web |title=Geothermal Technologies Program: Tapping the Earth’s energy to meet our heat and power needs |url=https://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy04osti/36025.pdf |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy, Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy |accessdate=June 2, 2018 |format=PDF |date=April 2004}}</ref> The second plant consists of two [[Binary cycle]] OECs and was placed in service in 2011 and commenced commercial operation in 2012. There is a plan to replace the first plant's ten old OECs with two new OECs which increase the generating capacity from 38 MW to 46 MW.<ref name=ar2017>{{cite web |publisher=Ormat Technologies |title=2017 Annual report |url=https://www.snl.com/interactive/newlookandfeel/4087066/2017_AR_Ormat.pdf}}</ref>
===Wells=== As of December 2017, there were six production wells and five [[injection well]]s in the Puna Complex.<ref name=ar2017/>
{| class="wikitable sortable" |+List of wells as of September 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.hawaii.gov/cab/files/2015/08/0008-02Review.DRAFT_.dl_.pdf|title=Noncovered Source Permit Review Summary (Renewal)|website=health.hawaii.gov}}</ref> |- ! Well !! Wellfield !! Type !! Depth !! Status after 2018 eruption |- | Kapoho State 1A (KS-1A)|| Pad A|| [[Injection well|Injection]]|| || |- | Kapoho State 3 (KS-3)|| Pad E || Injection|| || |- | Kapoho State 5 (KS-5) || Pad E|| Production|| || Covered by lava |- | Kapoho State 6 (KS-6)|| Pad E|| Production || {{convert|6532|ft|m}} || Covered by lava |- | Kapoho State 9 (KS-9)|| Pad A|| Production|| || |- | Kapoho State 10 (KS-10)|| Pad A|| Production || {{convert|5210|ft|m}} || |- | Kapoho State 11 (KS-11)|| Pad A|| Injection || {{convert|6500|ft|m}} || |- | Kapoho State 13 (KS-13)|| Pad A|| Injection || {{convert|8297|ft|m}} || |- | Kapoho State 14 (KS-14)|| Pad E|| Production|| || In proximity to magma |- | Kapoho State 15 (KS-15)|| Pad B|| Injection|| || |- | Kapoho State 16 (KS-16)|| Pad A|| Production|| || |- | Kapoho State 17 (KS-17)|| Pad E|| Production|| || |}
As of 2008, there are five active production wells all of which have a surface elevation of {{convert|620|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level and produce a mixture of steam and brine. The five wells produced an average of 600,000&nbsp;lb/hour (270,000&nbsp;kg/hour) of steam and 1,200,000&nbsp;lb/hour (545,000&nbsp;kg/hour) of brine. The temperature of fluids emerging from the production wells is approximately 640°F (338°C), which is returned to the injection wells at approximately 300–400°F (150–200°C) after being used to generate electricity.<ref name="Fitch and Matlick 2008">{{cite journal |last1=Fitch |first1=David |last2=Matlick |first2=Skip |title=Gold, silver and Other Metals in scale— Puna Geothermal Venture, Hawaii |journal=GRC Transactions |date=2008 |volume=32 |pages=385–388 |url=http://pubs.geothermal-library.org/lib/grc/1028353.pdf |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Direct uses"/>
===Alternative uses of geothermally-heated fluids=== In addition to electricity generation, additional uses of the facility have been suggested. A paper presented by Andrea Gill of the Hawaii Deptartment of Business, Economic Development, and Tourism—on behalf of a working group established to consider direct uses of the geothermal energy at PGV and its vicinity—outlined potential direct uses of the fluids at PGV as well as shallow groundwater wells in its vicinity, including fruit and [[macadamia nut]] dehydration, [[aquaculture]] and [[greenhouse]] heating, [[pasteurization]] and [[Sterilization (microbiology)|sterilization]], [[Hot spring|geothermal/health spas]], and [[geothermal heat pump]]s.<ref name="Direct uses">{{cite web |last1=Gill |first1=Andrea T. |title=Prospective Direct Use Enterprises in Kapoho, Hawaii |url=https://energy.hawaii.gov/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Prospective-Direct-Use-Enterprises-in-Kapoho-Hawaii.pdf |publisher=Hawaii Dept. of Business, Economic Development and Tourism, Strategic Industries Division |accessdate=June 2, 2018 |format=PDF |date=2004}}</ref> At PGV, hot brine after being utilized to generate electricity is approximately 300–400°F (150–200°C) when it is reinjected into the earth; the brine could be tapped for its thermal energy before being reinjected. Water wells under 750&nbsp;ft (230&nbsp;m) in the vicinity of PGV have recorded temperatures up to 193°F (89°C).<ref name="Direct uses"/>
In 2005, after a drill hit an uncommonly-observed type of magma, researchers and PGV expressed a desire to turn the borehole into an observatory for scientific studies.<ref name="Nature 2008"/>
